article.description: Swin Cash scored 22 points but Bill Laimbeer had to watch anxiously until Cash made a three-point play with 14.9 seconds left to help the Detroit Shock win their fourth straight, 72-68 over Indiana Fever on Saturday night.
article.headline: Cash's late 3-point play dooms Fever
article.linkText: Shock pull out fourth win in a row
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Swin Cash made her coach sweat out another win. She scored 22 points but Bill Laimbeer had to watch anxiously until Cash made a three-point play with 14.9 seconds left to help the Detroit Shock win their fourth straight, 72-68 over Indiana Fever on Saturday night. "One of these days, they have to make things easier on the coach," Laimbeer said. The defending WNBA champs lost key reserve Barb Farris to a dislocated left shoulder in the second half, but were still able to come from behind for the fourth game in a row. Ruth Riley had a regular-season career high with 26 points. Cash tied the game at 63 on a 3-pointer with 1:44 to go, and after a shot-clock violation, Ruth Riley gave the Shock their first lead of the game with two free throws. Riley fouled Tamika Catchings with 39.2 seconds to play, and she hit both shots to tie it. Cash missed at the other end, but Elaine Powell grabbed the offensive rebound and got the ball back to Detroit's captain. Cash made a layup as she was fouled by Kelly Schumacher. Indiana called a timeout they did not have on the ensuing inbounds play. Deanna Nolan missed the free throw, but the Shock also got the ball and put the game away from the line. "The soap opera continues," Cash said. "We wish we were playing games like we did last year, when we were beating teams by 15 points, but that's not going to be easy. We're the defending champs, and everyone is bringing their 'A' game against us." Natalie Williams led Indiana with 19 before fouling out in the final minute. "We are a younger team -- we've not been together as long as Detroit," Indiana coach Brian Winters said.

Game notes
Detroit Pistons forward Tayshaun Prince attended the game, one day before Game 4 of the NBA Finals. ... Indiana F Astou Ndiaye-Diatta, still the career games leader for Detroit, was presented with her 2003 championship ring before the game. ... With her first rebound, Williams became the first player in U.S. women's history to record 2,500 rebounds (ABL and WNBA combined).
